column3: History teacher Ron Jones, created the Third Wave experiment in order to demonstrate how people throughout history followed the crowd despite terrible things occurring. The Third Wave developed over such a short period of time because Jones was enforcing rules that gave the students a "supreme sense of discipline and community" (paragraph 2). Such rules included proper seating, classroom discipline, and saluting each other outside of the classroom. By implementing these rules, he became an authoritarian figure to whom his students became loyal. Soon, other students began joining and were being initiate based on what Mr. Jones was telling his students. This quick escalation caused Jones to end the experiment because he believed that it was getting out of control.
column4: History teacher Ron Jones created the Third Wave experiment to illustrate how people throughout history followed the crowd despite terrible events. The Third Wave emerged rapidly due to Jones's strict enforcement of rules that instilled fear within students. These rules, such as proper seating, classroom discipline, and a culture of loyalty and respect, created an authoritarian atmosphere that drew in students who were drawn to Jones's charisma and authority. However, as Jones's desire to maintain control grew, he ended the Third Wave experiment because he recognized that it was losing his grip on the students.
